title: Duke the Collie wins Australia's hardest working dog | 7NEWS
description: Duke the Collie from Stonehenge in Central Queensland has won Australia's Cobber Challenge, running 556 kilometres over three weeks to claim first prize. He becomes only the second Collie to win the prestigious working dog competition in its 10-year history. Owner Beck Smith runs her property largely alone and credits her working dogs with helping her through tough times, including recovery from catastrophic flooding earlier this year. title: Australian women are being promised more choice, for a lower cost, when accessing contraception
description: Australian women are being promised more choice, for a lower cost, when accessing contraception. description: Firefighters are battling a blaze at a waste centre in Spring Farm. Residents in the surrounding area of Sydney's southwest are being urged to close their windows as the blaze continues to burn. #springfarm #southwestsydney #sydney #fire #fireandrescue

title: ACCC takes Microsoft to court over misleading subscriptions | 7NEWS
description: The Australian Competition and Consumer Commission is taking Microsoft to federal court, alleging the tech giant misled 2.7 million Australian subscribers about their Office 365 subscription options. The ACCC claims Microsoft forced users to choose between upgrading to more expensive plans with AI co-pilot features or cancelling entirely, without disclosing cheaper 'classic plans' that maintained existing features at lower prices. Since co-pilot was added, subscription prices increased by $40-50, with the regulator seeking penalties, refunds and injunctions for affected consumers. title: Operation Trident nets 95 arrests in Sydney crime blitz | 7NEWS
description: Operation Trident, the state's first high visibility crime blitz, resulted in 95 arrests and 200 charges being laid. An extra 250 officers targeted domestic violence, drug supply, illegal tobacco and knife offences across Sydney, conducting more than 2,000 weapon scans and seizing 11 weapons. Sydneysiders can expect to see more of this style of operation targeting knife crime and youth crime.
